  <h2>Coastal vs. inland Tampa Bay maintenance cadence</h2>
  <p>Distance from the Gulf changes how often your condenser coil needs attention. Salt aerosol carries inland on the sea breeze and pits aluminum coil fins, copper refrigerant lines, and the galvanized cabinet of the outdoor unit. The closer to the water, the shorter the maintenance interval that actually prevents premature corrosion failure:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>0 to 5 miles from the coast (Clearwater, St. Pete Beach, Apollo Beach):</strong> Professional coil cleaning every 4 to 6 months. Annual tune-ups miss the second salt-season wave and let coil corrosion get ahead of you.</li>
    <li><strong>5 to 10 miles from the coast (west Tampa, parts of New Tampa):</strong> Every 6 months is the practical standard. Twice-a-year tune-ups catch salt-accelerated capacitor degradation before a mid-July no-cool call.</li>
    <li><strong>10 to 20 miles from the coast (Wesley Chapel, Land O' Lakes, Lutz, Zephyrhills):</strong> Standard twice-a-year tune-up cadence. Salt is a factor but not the dominant one - pine pollen, humidity biofilm, and runtime hours matter more.</li>
    <li><strong>20+ miles inland (east Pasco, <a href="/service-areas/polk-county-residential-ac-repair/">Polk County</a> interior):</strong> Once-a-year can work for newer equipment in protected locations, but twice a year is still the safer choice given Florida runtime hours.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If you are unsure where your home falls, measure the straight-line distance to the nearest tidal water on Google Maps. That is the number that matters for salt exposure, not the driving distance. This is also why we tailor cadence by neighborhood across <a href="/service-areas/wesley-chapel-ac-repair/">Wesley Chapel</a>, <a href="/service-areas/new-tampa-heating-and-cooling/">New Tampa</a>, and <a href="/service-areas/land-o-lakes-hvac-services/">Land O' Lakes</a> rather than selling one schedule to everyone.</p>

  <InContentCTA
